allow you to do those things.

00:13:51.226 --> 00:13:52.236 A:middle
But I'm curious about what

00:13:52.236 --> 00:13:53.416 A:middle
inspired this.

00:13:54.066 --> 00:13:55.886 A:middle
Whenever I see something unique

00:13:55.886 --> 00:13:57.816 A:middle
like this I wonder what's behind

00:13:57.816 --> 00:14:00.536 A:middle
it because it's unique and it's

00:13:57.816 --> 00:14:00.536 A:middle
it because it's unique and it's

00:14:00.536 --> 00:14:01.716 A:middle
implemented really well.

00:14:01.996 --> 00:14:03.786 A:middle
So I asked the developers of

00:14:03.786 --> 00:14:04.686 A:middle
Streaks Workout.

00:14:06.256 --> 00:14:09.436 A:middle
And it's such a common story to

00:14:09.436 --> 00:14:12.496 A:middle
hear about how an app originated

00:14:12.496 --> 00:14:14.066 A:middle
with an idea that came out of

00:14:14.066 --> 00:14:14.686 A:middle
prison.

00:14:17.266 --> 00:14:19.406 A:middle
So specifically, their idea

00:14:19.406 --> 00:14:21.196 A:middle
originated with how inmates in

00:14:21.196 --> 00:14:22.946 A:middle
prison keep workouts new and

00:14:22.946 --> 00:14:23.596 A:middle
interesting.

00:14:24.106 --> 00:14:25.526 A:middle
So I want to walk you through

00:14:25.656 --> 00:14:27.436 A:middle
how that works.

00:14:27.946 --> 00:14:30.616 A:middle
So in prison you take a normal

00:14:30.616 --> 00:14:31.786 A:middle
deck of cards and at the

00:14:31.786 --> 00:14:33.656 A:middle
beginning of each workout you

00:14:33.656 --> 00:14:35.136 A:middle
would assign a movement to each

00:14:35.136 --> 00:14:35.626 A:middle
suit.

00:14:35.996 --> 00:14:38.106 A:middle
So today diamonds are crunches.

00:14:39.006 --> 00:14:40.346 A:middle
The numbers on the cards

00:14:40.656 --> 00:14:42.356 A:middle
represent the number of reps per

00:14:42.356 --> 00:14:42.856 A:middle
movement.

00:14:43.146 --> 00:14:44.416 A:middle
So at the beginning of the

00:14:44.416 --> 00:14:46.456 A:middle
workout you'd put the deck face

00:14:46.456 --> 00:14:49.106 A:middle
down and you'd start drawing and

00:14:49.106 --> 00:14:50.206 A:middle
each card would deliver a

00:14:50.206 --> 00:14:51.566 A:middle
movement and a rep count.

00:14:51.816 --> 00:14:53.606 A:middle
OK, everyone eight crunches.

00:14:55.996 --> 00:14:58.096 A:middle
So the original app concept was

00:14:58.096 --> 00:15:00.056 A:middle
a literal recreation of this.

00:14:58.096 --> 00:15:00.056 A:middle
a literal recreation of this.

00:15:00.376 --> 00:15:02.086 A:middle
This is an early comp and they

00:15:02.086 --> 00:15:04.106 A:middle
also prototyped shuffling and

00:15:04.106 --> 00:15:08.276 A:middle
flipping cards to try to kind of

00:15:08.276 --> 00:15:11.706 A:middle
replicate the origin of this

00:15:11.706 --> 00:15:12.556 A:middle
prison workout.

00:15:12.936 --> 00:15:14.466 A:middle
But they quickly moved past the

00:15:14.466 --> 00:15:15.566 A:middle
literal approach.

00:15:16.256 --> 00:15:17.876 A:middle
They didn't stick to the literal

00:15:17.876 --> 00:15:19.416 A:middle
deck of cards because it carried

00:15:19.416 --> 00:15:20.666 A:middle
too many constraints.

00:15:21.036 --> 00:15:22.606 A:middle
Four suits would limit the

00:15:22.606 --> 00:15:23.686 A:middle
number of movements that you

00:15:23.686 --> 00:15:25.026 A:middle
could do in each workout and

00:15:25.026 --> 00:15:26.266 A:middle
people would somehow need to

00:15:26.266 --> 00:15:28.086 A:middle
remember that diamonds

00:15:28.086 --> 00:15:29.546 A:middle
represented crunches in that

00:15:29.546 --> 00:15:31.386 A:middle
particular workout and that's

00:15:31.386 --> 00:15:32.136 A:middle
work, right?

00:15:33.496 --> 00:15:35.056 A:middle
So instead they focused on the

00:15:35.056 --> 00:15:36.626 A:middle
value that they wanted to bring.

00:15:38.236 --> 00:15:39.586 A:middle
They wanted to help people make

00:15:39.586 --> 00:15:41.066 A:middle
a habit of working out.

00:15:42.446 --> 00:15:44.616 A:middle
So they acknowledged that people

00:15:44.616 --> 00:15:46.516 A:middle
felt inertia when they were

00:15:46.516 --> 00:15:47.846 A:middle
going to launch a workout app

00:15:48.126 --> 00:15:49.846 A:middle
and they removed as much as

00:15:49.846 --> 00:15:51.466 A:middle
possible that might trigger that

00:15:52.146 --> 00:15:53.446 A:middle
and they stayed true to the

00:15:53.446 --> 00:15:55.366 A:middle
original intent of the prison

00:15:55.366 --> 00:15:57.226 A:middle
workout, which is that spirit of

00:15:57.226 --> 00:15:58.816 A:middle
randomness and surprise.

00:15:59.476 --> 00:16:01.656 A:middle
And that's what I mean by deep

00:15:59.476 --> 00:16:01.656 A:middle
And that's what I mean by deep

00:16:01.656 --> 00:16:02.376 A:middle
understanding.

00:16:02.376 --> 00:16:03.806 A:middle
Knowing the person that you want

00:16:03.806 --> 00:16:05.476 A:middle
to reach and the actual problem

00:16:05.476 --> 00:16:06.436 A:middle
that they might have.

00:16:06.906 --> 00:16:08.476 A:middle
So the superficial approach to

00:16:08.476 --> 00:16:10.076 A:middle
this workout would have been

00:16:10.076 --> 00:16:11.286 A:middle
just a typical workout app,

00:16:11.356 --> 00:16:11.646 A:middle
right?

00:16:11.936 --> 00:16:13.036 A:middle
Of course people want to get

00:16:13.036 --> 00:16:13.516 A:middle
healthy.

00:16:14.046 --> 00:16:15.756 A:middle
But what people really want, or

00:16:15.756 --> 00:16:17.326 A:middle
what I really want anyway is to

00:16:17.326 --> 00:16:19.286 A:middle
get past the boredom and that

00:16:19.286 --> 00:16:20.626 A:middle
inertia and they've addressed

00:16:20.656 --> 00:16:21.306 A:middle
that for me.

00:16:23.156 --> 00:16:27.306 A:middle
So knowing users is nothing new.

00:16:27.546 --> 00:16:30.386 A:middle
I'm guessing a lot of you here

00:16:30.386 --> 00:16:32.726 A:middle
have personas and market

00:16:32.726 --> 00:16:35.106 A:middle
segments and you do surveys and

00:16:35.106 --> 00:16:36.796 A:middle
other kinds of user research

00:16:36.916 --> 00:16:38.336 A:middle
focus groups.

00:16:38.616 --> 00:16:40.326 A:middle
Maybe you create experience maps

00:16:40.326 --> 00:16:41.846 A:middle
and customer journeys and user

00:16:41.846 --> 00:16:42.536 A:middle
stories.

00:16:43.176 --> 00:16:45.086 A:middle
All of those can be useful

00:16:45.086 --> 00:16:45.616 A:middle
models.

00:16:46.656 --> 00:16:48.266 A:middle
But they have to feel authentic,

00:16:48.436 --> 00:16:48.776 A:middle
right?

00:16:48.776 --> 00:16:50.716 A:middle
They actually have to feel like

00:16:50.866 --> 00:16:51.366 A:middle
people.

00:16:52.776 --> 00:16:54.776 A:middle
That can make focus easier and

00:16:54.776 --> 00:16:56.316 A:middle
it can help teams kind of come

00:16:56.316 --> 00:16:57.966 A:middle
together around a vision.

00:16:57.966 --> 00:16:59.676 A:middle
As long as you share a common

00:16:59.676 --> 00:17:01.856 A:middle
understanding and you feel a

00:16:59.676 --> 00:17:01.856 A:middle
understanding and you feel a

00:17:01.856 --> 00:17:04.356 A:middle
real empathy for the person that

00:17:04.356 --> 00:17:05.576 A:middle
you're designing for.

00:17:05.915 --> 00:17:06.705 A:middle
Those can work.

00:17:07.945 --> 00:17:10.935 A:middle
But too often those artifacts of

00:17:10.935 --> 00:17:12.836 A:middle
needs and goals and skills, they

00:17:12.836 --> 00:17:14.165 A:middle
just feel artificial.

00:17:14.906 --> 00:17:16.685 A:middle
They may not connect with

00:17:16.685 --> 00:17:17.286 A:middle
everyone.

00:17:17.685 --> 00:17:19.816 A:middle
They feel complicated or distant

00:17:19.816 --> 00:17:20.576 A:middle
or corny.

00:17:21.205 --> 00:17:24.036 A:middle
So for a moment I want to talk

00:17:24.036 --> 00:17:26.586 A:middle
about how much easier it is to

00:17:26.586 --> 00:17:28.376 A:middle
make some something when you

00:17:28.376 --> 00:17:30.226 A:middle
really care about the person

00:17:30.226 --> 00:17:31.266 A:middle
you're making it for.

00:17:32.756 --> 00:17:34.286 A:middle
So I first heard about this

00:17:34.286 --> 00:17:35.316 A:middle
story that I'm going to tell you

00:17:35.316 --> 00:17:35.836 A:middle
in a book.

00:17:35.976 --> 00:17:38.146 A:middle
It's by a guy named Alan Cooper,

00:17:38.486 --> 00:17:40.296 A:middle
he's a software developer from

00:17:40.296 --> 00:17:42.816 A:middle
the early days, and his claim to

00:17:42.816 --> 00:17:44.686 A:middle
fame is that he created a

00:17:44.686 --> 00:17:47.276 A:middle
prototype that became Visual

00:17:47.276 --> 00:17:47.786 A:middle
Basic.

00:17:48.246 --> 00:17:50.776 A:middle
And this is an actual pixel

00:17:50.976 --> 00:17:53.646 A:middle
